<div class="prose">

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Why these words?</div>
  <p>This unit teaches you to read a landscape the way a geologist does — to see the history of erosion, deposition, climate, and human impact written into a place. You will produce a "biography" of a Chennai-area location. The vocabulary below is the working language of landscape reading.</p>
</div>

<h2>Vocabulary</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Term</th>
      <th>What it means + visual cue</th>
      <th>Sentence stem</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Weathering</strong></td>
      <td>The breaking down of rocks at the Earth's surface by water, ice, temperature change, plants, or chemicals. Different from erosion. <em>Visual: Rock cracking from ice expansion in winter.</em></td>
      <td>This rock shows evidence of weathering by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Erosion</strong></td>
      <td>The movement of weathered material from one place to another by water, wind, ice, or gravity. <em>Visual: Stream carrying sediment downhill.</em></td>
      <td>Erosion at this location is caused mainly by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Deposition</strong></td>
      <td>When eroded material is dropped and accumulates somewhere new. Beaches, deltas, and floodplains are deposition features. <em>Visual: River slowing down at its mouth, dropping sand to form a delta.</em></td>
      <td>This is a deposition landform because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Sediment</strong></td>
      <td>Particles of rock, mineral, or organic material that have been weathered, eroded, and deposited. <em>Visual: Layered jar of sand, silt, and clay.</em></td>
      <td>The sediment here is mostly ___, which tells us ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Landform</strong></td>
      <td>A natural feature of the Earth's surface — mountain, valley, beach, delta, plateau, etc. <em>Visual: Six small icons: mountain, valley, delta, beach, dune, cliff.</em></td>
      <td>The dominant landform at this site is a ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Geologic time</strong></td>
      <td>The vast timescale of Earth's history (billions of years), in which slow processes produce huge changes. <em>Visual: Clock face where one second equals millions of years.</em></td>
      <td>Over geologic time, this landscape has ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Stratigraphy</strong></td>
      <td>The study of rock layers. Older layers sit below younger ones; reading them tells the order of past events. <em>Visual: Cake cross-section with labeled layers, oldest at bottom.</em></td>
      <td>The stratigraphy here shows that ___ happened before ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Geomorphology</strong></td>
      <td>The study of how landforms develop and change over time. <em>Visual: Time-lapse arrow showing a hill eroding into a valley.</em></td>
      <td>Geomorphology tells us this landscape formed by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Monsoon</strong></td>
      <td>A seasonal wind pattern that brings heavy rain to South and Southeast Asia. Drives much of the surface change in Chennai. <em>Visual: Curved arrow showing wind reversing direction with the seasons over India.</em></td>
      <td>The monsoon affects this location by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Watershed</strong></td>
      <td>The area of land where all water drains to a single river, lake, or sea. Also called a drainage basin. <em>Visual: Bowl shape with arrows flowing toward a central stream.</em></td>
      <td>This site sits in the ___ watershed, which drains to ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Coastline</strong></td>
      <td>The boundary between land and sea. Constantly changing through erosion, deposition, and sea-level change. <em>Visual: Wavy line where waves meet beach.</em></td>
      <td>This coastline is advancing / retreating because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Aquifer</strong></td>
      <td>An underground layer of rock or sediment that holds and transmits groundwater. <em>Visual: Cross-section showing water-filled porous rock below the surface.</em></td>
      <td>The aquifer beneath this location is ___ and is recharged by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Sea-level change</strong></td>
      <td>Long-term rise or fall in the average height of the ocean surface. Caused by ice volume, thermal expansion, and tectonics. <em>Visual: Two horizontal lines on a coastline — past and present sea level.</em></td>
      <td>Sea-level change at this site means ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Human modification</strong></td>
      <td>Changes to a landscape caused by people — building, draining, dredging, paving, planting, mining. <em>Visual: Bulldozer and concrete next to natural ground.</em></td>
      <td>Humans have modified this location by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Projection</strong></td>
      <td>A scientifically-grounded prediction of future change based on current trends and models. <em>Visual: Graph with solid past line and dashed future line.</em></td>
      <td>Projections suggest this location will ___ by ___.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">In-class pre-teach activity (10 min)</div>
  <p><strong>Photo-walk.</strong> I will show you 3 photographs of Chennai-area locations. For each photo, write 3 vocabulary terms that apply and one sentence explaining what story the landscape is telling.</p>
</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Paired discussion prompt</div>
  <p>With a partner: take turns describing what you would expect to see at one of the 9 Unit 2 location options if you visited it. Use at least 4 terms from this list. Your partner's job is to listen and ask "how do you know?" after each claim.</p>
</div>

